{{otherpersons|Edward Litton}}
'''Sir Henry Hervey Bruce, 3rd Baronet''' (22 Sep 1820 <U+2013> 8 Dec 1907)<ref name="rayment-hc">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ccommons5.htm|title=House of Commons constituencies beginning with "C" (part 5)|work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons page|accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref> was an Irish [[Irish Conservative Party|Conservative]] politician. He was [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Coleraine (UK Parliament constituency)|Coleraine]] from 1862 to 1874, and from 1880 to 1885.

Bruce was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] at an unopposed by-election in 1862, following the death of the Conservative MP [[John Boyd (Irish politician)|John Boyd]].<ref name="walker-1801-1922">{{cite book
 | title  = Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801<U+2013>1922
 | editor = Brian M. Walker
 | publisher = Royal Irish Academy
 | location  = Dublin
 | date      = 1978
 | isbn      = 0 901714 12 7
 | pages     = 99
}}</ref> He was re-elected unopposed at the general elections in [[United Kingdom general election, 1865|1865]] and [[United Kingdom general election, 1868|1868]],<ref>Walker, op. cit., pages 102&198</ref> but was defeated at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1874|1874 general election]] by the Liberal candidate [[Daniel Taylor (politician)|Daniel Taylor]].<ref>Walker, op. cit., pages 115</ref> He defeated Taylor (by 222 votes to 193) at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1880|1880 general election]], and held the seat until the borough of [[Coleraine]] lost its separate parliamentary representation at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1885|1885 general election]].<ref name="rayment-hc" />

He was [[Lord Lieutenant of Londonderry]] from 1877 to 1907, and was sworn of the [[Privy Council of Ireland]] in 1889.<ref name="rayment-bt">{{cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/baronetage/baronetsB6.htm |title=Baronetcies beginning with "B" (part 6)|work=Leigh Rayment's Baronetage pages |accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref>

